  • Create a season (Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter) variable. Calculate the length of stays by season. Which season has the longest length of stays on average?

Summer has the longest average length of stays.

df18$season <- case_when(
  df18$moa %in% c(12,1,2)  ~ 'Winter',
  df18$moa %in% c(3,4,5)~ 'Spring',
  df18$moa %in% c(6,7,8)~ 'Summer',
  TRUE ~ 'Fall')
df18 %>% group_by(season) %>% summarise(average_los = mean(los)) %>% arrange(-average_los)

  • Through this preliminary exploration, I was able to learn some interesting things about the data. I learned about the different patient admission trends. For example, October was the month that had the most patient admissions while March was the monch with the most female teenager patient admissions. I also learned that January has the oldest patients on average, and that men in this dataset are slightly older than women on average. Lastly, creating the season variable allowed me to see that summer had the greatest average length of stay. Overall, this exploration helped me understand the data and helped me think about what visualizations I could produce that would provide further insight into the dataset.

# how does los differ for different sexes? 

df18$sex <- as.character(df18$sex)
  
df18 %>% filter( sex == "1" | sex == "2") %>% ggplot()+
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = los, y = sex)) + xlim(0,12) +   labs(x='Length of Stay (Days)', 
       y = 'Sex (1 = Male, 2 = Female)', 
       title = 'Boxplot of the Length of Stay by Sex', 
       caption = 'Men Have a Slightly Higher Length of Stay on Average')
## Warning: Removed 7911 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

 # Length of stay for each age per season
df18$raceethn <- as.character(df18$raceethn)

df18 %>% group_by(age, season) %>% summarise(average_stay=mean(los)) %>% 
  ggplot()+ 
  geom_col(mapping=aes(x=age, y=average_stay, fill = season)) + labs(x='Age', 
       y = 'Length of Stay (Days)', 
       title = 'Average Length of Stay in each Season per Age', 
       caption = 'Ages 7-17 Have the Longest Average Lengths of Stay')

df18$admission_reason <- ifelse(df18$diag_adm == "Z3800" ,"Vaginal Infant Delivery",
                  ifelse(df18$diag_adm  == "Z3801" , "C-Section Infant Delivery",
                   ifelse(df18$diag_adm  == "R0602" , "Shortness of breath",
                    ifelse(df18$diag_adm  == "J189" , "Pneumonia",
                           ifelse(df18$diag_adm  == "R079" , "Chest pain",
                              "Other")))))
df18 %>% filter(admission_reason %in% c("Shortness of breath", "Pneumonia","Chest pain")) %>%  ggplot()+ 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=age), fill = 'salmon') + facet_wrap(~admission_reason)+ labs(x='Age', 
       y = 'Admitted Patient Count', 
       title = 'Age Distributions of Common Hospital Admissions', 
       caption = 'There are clear trends in the most commonly admitted age range for each admission reason.')

  • Summary: I began by looking at the length of stay by sex and found that men stay longer on average than women do. I then looked at the length of stay by age and by season, where I found that ages 7-17 have the longest lengths of stay. This made me wonder what these ages were most commonly admitted for. I found and plotted the top 6 reasons for ages 7-17 to be admitted, which included major depressive disorder, disruptive mood dysregulation disorder, adjustment disorder (AD), and homicidal and suicidal ideations. Because 3 out of 6 of the reasons were depression, I looked at the age distribution of these three depression codes and found that depression is most prevalent in teens, and has a big drop off after age 55. I then wondered why individuals in general were commonly admitted into the hospital. The common reasons were infant delivery, shortness of breath, pneumonia, and chest pain. I returned to exploring mental health and wanted to look at seasonal trends of mental health related hospital admissions. I found as many hospital codes related to mental health as I could online and created a variable that signified if this patient was admitted for a mental health reason. I then plotted the amount of admissions against the months in 2018. I saw peaks in January and May. I then binned age so I could view the same trend but by age group. I then looked into location, and found that Massachusetts, Connecticut, and Rhode Island follow similar mental health admission trends, peaking in either may or June. I took a look at race and found the data set was largely white patients. I then plotted the average length of stay against the total charge for each race. The variables appear to be positively correlated (longer stay = higher charge) for all races. Finally, I created a bar race that shows the average total charge for each race in every month.

- Using caret for this question. Set Training Control to be: Use Cross-Validation of 5 folds across all models. Train & tune at least 3 different models (i.e. three different values for method= in the train function of caret). Plot the hyper-parameter tuning plots for each model.

# Decide the range of the maxdepth to search for the best
tuneGrid = expand.grid(maxdepth = 2:10)
# Cross-Validation
trControl = trainControl(method = "cv",
                         number = 5)
# first approach
approach1 <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                                method = "rpart2", 
                                trControl = trControl,
                                tuneGrid = tuneGrid)

# Plot the results

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target, positive = "high")

Findings:

The most important predictors in determining the total charge was length of stay, the type of admission, and the provider. The models were able to predict whether the charge was above the median with 84% accuracy based on these and other features. The next model I created was one that predicts whether the patoent is an adult or a minor. The most important features in this model were the type of administration, campus, and provider. This model was able to predict extremely well, with a top accuracy of 99% using the decision tree method.
